Its not completely the original design, but what it evolved into. And 
since we don&#39;t have yet a complete suite of tests, we&#39;re reluctant to make 
large-scale refactorings  to the code.
Back to the original question (where to put the test classes), I prefer 
keeping them near the actual code (=the same package). This way these 
classes are never &quot;outsiders&quot;, and you tend to look at them and update 
them as part of the project itself.





&quot;Jason Rogers&quot; &lt;jason.rogers@...&gt;
11/06/2001 16:08
Please respond to junit


        To:     &quot;&#39;junit@yahoogroups.com&#39;&quot; &lt;junit@yahoogroups.com&gt;
        cc: 
        Subject:        RE: [junit] Best Practice for Tests ?


IMO...

    &gt; It simply make testing easier, without changing the protection of
existing code.
    &gt; We find it sometimes easy to test part of a flow (which usually
resides in a separate method) rather than
    &gt; check the public interface function.

Then shouldn&#39;t these be made part of the public interface and allow the
client to interact with them?  If the client has no business touching 
these
parts, make them private.

    &gt; Also, I take the term &quot;public interface&quot; as relative. If an object
exposes an interface (set of methods)
    &gt; to its peer objects within its package, I see no reason not to test
it, even though those methods are
    &gt; package-protected.

I guess I disagree here.  I am not convinced that package-potected methods
are part of a public interface.  If they are used that way I would 
question
whether some refactoring needed to take place.  But that&#39;s just my 
opinion.
I don&#39;t want to seem like I am picking on your design decisions.

-Jason


